{{Other uses|National Restoration Party (disambiguation)}} {{Infobox political party | country = Costa Rica | flag = Restauracionnacional.jpg | colorcode = #0059CF | name = National Restoration party |native_name = Partido Restauración Nacional | foundation = 5 February 2005<ref name="tsern">[https://www.tse.go.cr/restauracionnacional.htm Partido Político Restauración Nacional] Tribunal Supremo de Elecciones. Retrieved: 2014-03-05. {{es}}</ref> | president = [https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carlos_Avenda%C3%B1o_Calvo Carlos Avendaño Calvo] <ref> https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carlos_Avenda%C3%B1o_Calvo</ref> | secretary_general = Mónica Catalán Marín | ideology = [[Conservatism]]<ref>[http://www.tse.go.cr/pdf/normativa/estatutos/restauracionnacional.pdf Estatuto Partido Restauración Nacional] Tribunal Supremo de Elecciones. Retrieved: 2014-05-10. {{es}}</ref> |religion = [[Evangelical Christianity]] | position = [[Right-wing]] to [[Far right]]<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2018/mar/30/gender-ideology-big-bogus-and-coming-to-a-fear-campaign-near-you 'Gender ideology': big, bogus and coming to a fear campaign near you] the Guardian</ref> | international = | colours = [[Yellow]] and [[blue]] |seats1_title = [[Legislative Assembly of Costa Rica|Legislative Assembly]] |seats1 = {{Composition bar|7|57|#0059CF}} }}
The '''National Restoration Party''' (''{{lang-es|Partido Restauración Nacional}}'' – PRN) is a political party in [[Costa Rica]]. It was founded in 2005 by [https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carlos_Avenda%C3%B1o_Calvo|Carlos Avendaño Calvo] mostly by dissidents of Costa Rica's historical [[Christian politics|Christian party]], [[Costa Rican Renewal Party|Costa Rican Renewal]], after its then only deputy,[https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carlos_Avenda%C3%B1o_Calvo|Carlos Avendaño Calvo], left.<ref name="tsern" /> Avendaño would successfully return to Congress because of the party from 2010 to 2014. Even though he had personal differences with [[Justo Orozco]] (then the PRC's only deputy), both were able to work together in defending the same agenda, mainly the conservative views of the [[evangelical Christians|evangelical community]]. The party's candidate in the [[Costa Rican general election, 2014|presidential election of 2014]] was Avendaño, who received 1.35 percent of the vote.<ref>[http://svr.tse.go.cr/aplicacionvisualizador/pdfs/e88e50d285bef1250fbac75ff2561e33.pdf Resultados Electorales: Total General] Tribunal Supremo de Elecciones. 2014-02-17. {{es}}</ref>
In the same year's [[Costa Rican general election, 2014|parliamentary election]], [[Gerardo Fabricio Alvarado Muñoz]], representing [[San José Province|San José]], was elected to the only seat in the [[Legislative Assembly of Costa Rica|Legislative Assembly]] that was won by the party.<ref>[http://www.asamblea.go.cr/Diputadas_Diputados/Documents/Declatoria_diputados_2014-2018.pdf Declaratoria de elección de Diputados a la Asamblea Legislativa de la República de Costa Rica 2014-2018] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304090239/http://www.asamblea.go.cr/Diputadas_Diputados/Documents/Declatoria_diputados_2014-2018.pdf |date=2016-03-04 }} Tribunal Supremo de Elecciones, 2014-03-03. {{es}}</ref>
In the [[Costa Rican general election, 2018|2018 Costa Rican general elections]] the party when it won 14 of the parliament seats and its presidential candidate, [[Fabricio Alvarado]], went in to the runoff.<ref>https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-42938510</ref> According to the BBC, his campaign gained in popularity because of his opposition to [[same-sex marriage]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Costa Rica election: Gay marriage debate dominates campaign|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-42938510|date=4 February 2018|accessdate=4 February 2018|work=BBC News Online|page=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-42938510}}</ref> The party also holds anti-inmigration positions and calls for closed borders and harsher controls on migrants.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chinchilla |first1=Aaron |title=Restauración Nacional exige al Gobierno reforzar controles migratorios en Peñas Blancas |agency=El Periódico |date=25 July 2018}}</ref>
==Controversies==
In March 2018, the newspaper ''Semanario Universidad'' reported that high figures of the party had billed several million [[Costa Rican colón|colones]] for professional services for participating in their own campaign such as the beneficiaries' own candidate, Fabricio Alvarado, his wife, his brothers, his two vice-presidential nominees, two sons, and the ex-wife of the party president, [[https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carlos_Avendano_Calvo|Carlos Avendaño]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Murillo|first1=Alvaro|last2=Miranda|first2=Hulda|last3=Salazar|first3=Daniel|title=Restauración reporta al TSE pagos a Fabricio y sus vicepresidentes por alquilar carros a la campaña|url=https://semanariouniversidad.com/pais/restauracion-reporta-al-tse-pagos-a-fabricio-y-sus-vicepresidentes-por-alquilar-carros-a-la-campana/|accessdate=25 May 2018|agency=Semanario Universidad|date=27 March 2018}}</ref> It was later discovered that one of the beneficiaries, the son of Avendaño, had received professional services for working for the party while he was incapacitated by health from his official work at the [[Costa Rican Institute of Electricity]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Hijo de diputado trabajo para restauracion|url=https://www.nacion.com/el-pais/politica/hijo-de-diputado-trabajo-para-restauracion/SR5HWZAOCVH63BILIYHXV7A7WY/story/|accessdate=25 May 2018|agency=La Nación}}</ref> In May 2018, it was reported that the party had hired the polling company OPol, according to financial reports submitted to the [[Tribunal Supremo de Elecciones de Costa Rica|Supreme Electoral Tribunal]]. Although party officials originally reported that they were political consultancies unrelated to the polls, subsequent investigations by the newspaper ''[[La Nación (Costa Rica)|La Nación]]'' discovered a contract for the payment of the six surveys that were conducted during the second round campaign, five of which were published and all of which Alvarado appeared as frontrunner by a large margin.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cambronero|first1=Natasha|title=Encuestas de Opol se hicieron por encargo de Restauración Nacional de cara a la segunda ronda|url=https://www.nacion.com/el-pais/politica/encuestas-de-opol-se-hicieron-por-encargo-de/67BL2AJD2FGCPHG7CMMIPTCXFU/story/|accessdate=25 May 2018|agency=La Nación|date=25 May 2018}}</ref> Previously, the pollster had already been in controversy after it was reported on social networks that a company vehicle driven by director Mauricio Muñoz, had carried party flags.
In late May, Avendaño himself filed a complaint with the Supreme Electoral Tribunal for what he called a "parallel structure" made up of the campaign team of the candidate for hiring outside the ethical controls stipulated by the party that would have been the one that negotiated those and other payments.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cambronero|first1=Natasha|last2=Sequeira|first2=Aarón|title=Carlos Avendaño denuncia 'estructura paralela' en financiamiento de campaña de Fabricio Alvarado|url=https://www.nacion.com/el-pais/politica/carlos-avendano-denuncia-estructura-paralela-en/WKZSHZK5K5GN7KXXIHJXMBPUPY/story/|accessdate=30 May 2018|agency=La Nación|date=29 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Oviedo|first1=Esteban|last2=Cambronero|first2=Natasha|last3=Sequeira|first3=Aarón|title=Empresa de cantante reclama ¢115 millones a Restauración y anuncia demanda en tribunales|url=https://www.nacion.com/el-pais/politica/empresa-de-cantante-reclama-115-millones-a/EEVZTURINFDNDOWK2YKRVBAQJY/story/|accessdate=30 May 2018|agency=La Nación}}</ref>
